For this course, even though there are video lessons, the teaching approach is like that of reading the module in paraphrase, lacking explanation and interactive points - that is why the learning experience is 1 out of 5. For the short quizzes, assignments, and activities, I noticed many errors, either typographical or incomplete questions. I also encountered questions that were not discussed/related to the module objectives or questions that would be discussed in later modules but appeared earlier in the short quizzes, assignments or activities part. I do not find the module very helpful as I use other textbooks to understand the topics being discussed like the worksheet, which is not properly explained how to use, how to apply, or how to begin with but still came up as an activity exercise. As frustrating as it can be, I still do appreciate the effort of the mentor to explain some of the questions that I raised in Help Center section. I suggest that the organizers make an option for students to check their answers because there is still room for slight errors in encoding the quizzes section in the LMS. This is for the purpose of grade transparency and feedback to the student. I also suggest that the Course and Mentor Evaluation be moved last so that we can include feedback for the final exam and the course project, whether the content is relevant/related to the objectives of the lessons discussed in each module. Thank you and I hope you have the time to read this so that this course may be improved.

The course is terrible, majority of the questions in the identification segments of the tests are inaccurate, an example:

In one of the questions it asks
"It detects all words in O(n + m + z) time, where n is the text length"

The answer to this is the "Aho-corasick algorithm".
However the test views this as incorrect. When i went to try multiple times as this is test allows me to, apparently the answer is "aho-corasick" with seemingly no other alternatives.

Normally I could overlook this sort of error as identification tests online (as my understanding goes) requires the professor to input a number of correct answers, for example "Aho-corasick algorithm" "Aho Corasick Algorithm" and so on, I can understand that there are times where it is case sensitive, or a matter of misspelling. What I cannot accept however, is the numerous times that the tests under this course repeats this instance multiple times. I cannot count the number of times that I flagged questions in this course

MY SUGGESTION
My suggestions are that this course must take away all of the identification questions OR have the answers go through strict screening and double checking, as the test is very infuriating to go through. Additionally majority of the questions in each of the tests have either broken english, or clearly have been copy pasted so those must go through rigorous screening as well.

Final notes:
I am unsure, but i am banking this on a guess as this has not been the first course to be this terrible.
I believe that the courses placed under this professor all suffer from the same problem, note that i DO NOT have a problem with the professor, rather I do have a MASSIVE problem with the content of the course, as it is without a doubt, unfair

column8: Concise, direct to the point and informative

Learning did not feel like a chore as I genuinely enjoyed the content within the course's modules. The course modules were well-written, thorough and informative. 

A huge issue for me, however, is the inaccuracy of the assignments/short and long quizzes. I've encountered a lot of errors within the mentioned and it's irritating to see a low score and the lowering of my grade when I know FOR CERTAIN that I should've had a higher score because I was right. I won't tell too much examples ( as there were quite many ) but another example of this issue of mine is within the week 15-16. When asked which, of the following listed, DOES NOT belong to the Six Arts, the choice "sports" was marked as incorrect when it SHOULD HAVE BEEN the CORRECT answer. The choice "music" was marked as correct however, music DOES BELONG to the Six Arts. The exam is wrong and gave me a low score when I should've gotten a higher one. PLEASE kindly fix this and DOUBLE-CHECK the exams/modules for accuracy before providing them to students. We, parents and working-students, pay our hard-earned money for our tuition. ( WHICH IS NOT CHEAP AT ALL, BY THE WAY ) Therefore, we should be given the best possible experience. 

Nonetheless, if I had more time, I would've created a ticket and reported the matter. Unfortunately, it would take too much time and I am in a hurry to simply just finish the module and move on to the next semester. Therefore, though I should have gotten a higher grade, I'll let this issue pass. In order to avoid these kinds of issues in the future, however, as previously mentioned, kindly remember to double-check the modules, assignments, activities etc. before providing them to students.

The true or false question, "Swimmer's knee is pain that is commonly associated to the breast stroke" marked my "True" answer as incorrect when according to the module, it IS TRUE that Swimmer's knee is pain that is commonly associated with the breast stroke. Why am I and my grade for the subject suffering for the negligence and carelessness of whoever made the assignments, short and long quizzes? 

Honestly speaking, this subject's modules aren't that great. They're messy, unfinished and unprofessional. For example, the third module, "Module 003 Common Injuries; Preventions" still has the note for the Mentor and/or module writer. It states that "the file should be saved using the format: Week<XX>-Module" and that "there should only be one file for module per week", among others, which I strongly don't think is intended for the students to read and therefore, should have been edited out. Frankly, it seems that the modules for this subject were rushed. 

Make sure to double-check the learning modules, assignments, short and long quizzes etc. that you provide to your students. We pay good money for our courses and therefore accordingly, we should be served the best quality as well. What a disappointment to see my hard-earned money wasted on a greedy institution that clearly does not value its students. Rather, it's very clear priority is to simply milk money from working-students, parents etc.. 

If only I had the time to do so, I would have made a ticket and reported it. However, I'm in a hurry to simply get my subjects done with and move on with the next chapter in my life. For the benefit of future AMA OEd students, however, make a mental note to double-check the learning materials and ensure that they are of best quality before handing them out. Keep in mind that the tuition in AMA is not cheap. I am not attacking your institution. I am providing criticism in order you to do better. The least you can do is make an effort.

Course content was poorly written, vague, and at times had no correlation to the tests that were given.

1. The way it (collation of all content) was written presents itself as evidently unchecked, unedited, and blatantly disregarded. There was a lack of sufficient proof reading that went into the modules. The presentations could be sufficient as is, if it could supplement (or vice versa) the content of the modules. The modules were also written as if someone from grade 7 was tasked to transcribe a script for a Youtube video. Evidence enough is in the wording, grammar, and use (or lack thereof) of commas. Luckily, I was able to somehow understand the content given in these modules, however, it remains that the effectivity, quality, and presentation of the content is EXTREMELY DISAPPOINTING.

2. Tests. These were unbearably frustrating. Perhaps the issue is in the way I process the questions, or my own views not aligning with the fact of the questions, but I can attribute it absolutely on the disconnect of the CONTENT provided in the MODULES and PRESENTATIONS, even the supplementary videos (and other reading materials that were paraphrased into the module). I can say confidently that the way the QUESTIONS were WRITTEN are of the same POOR QUALITY as the MODULES. 

I gathered a little bit of evidence on the flagged questions of "Long Test 003" to be presented here:

I. "Which of the following describes the process in which issues and concerns are aired by political parties thru the instrumentation of government?

a. hearings
b. platforms
c. propaganda
d. representation "

(1) The answer for this was "Platforms" , and I can argue that the question should've been reframed as:

II. "Which of the following best describes the medium wherein political parties air issues and concerns through and to the Government?"

(2) Why is it exactly "Platforms" ? How is that considered a process? Is that not a medium? Hearings (like congressional hearings) are part of a process, if not the the act alone of airing issues and concerns to and through the Government.

(3) The spelling alone of "thru" instead of it being "through" should be proof enough that the questions were NOT proofread.

(4) The question itself could have been fine, were it not for the answers being VAGUE or BROAD. "PLATFORMS" is an example of this already.

Which among the following details the policy a certain political party has and is identified to such?

a. politics
b. beliefs
c. values
d. Platform 

(1) Just, what?

(2) "Which among the following describes a political party's policy?" Would have been enough.

III. Younger generations are sufficiently represented in party membership, leadership and legislatures.

(1) This where the realm of subjectivity and objectivity blurs. While the objective intent is to represent the majority of the youth, the reality is they are not. However, this question would be better presented as an essay-type question, rather than a "true or false" question.

(2) If I wanted subjectivity, I would have rather written an essay instead.

IV. The feature of a poor and resilient democracy is based on inclusiveness. (True or False)

(1) It may be due to conflicting methods of societal analysis, but the framing of the question is appalling.

(2) When creating a TRUE or FALSE question, we don't put it out there the exact passages of the reading material, as it would most likely be assumed to be an actual question STATING that poor and (but) resilient democracies are based on the inclusivity of the people.

(3) Simply switching one word, in this case being "poor", is a poor attempt at creating a filler question. Honestly, put some effort into it, as it reflects poorly on the school.

(4) I interpreted this question as if it were as is: as any nation, irrespective of their economic situation, for as long as it claims to practice democracy, it will undeniably be based on inclusivity. So any nation, even if poor, has a democracy based on inclusivity. There are poorer nations who evidently practice more democracy than America and the Philippines combined. If you feel the need to debate this, it proves my point that the question is framed too subjectively and/or poorly thought of.

There are many more examples I could list in this course, but I hope this gets somewhere. Otherwise it's the Dean I'll have to contact directly regarding these concerns.

column8:
The experience I had while in this course was middling, and at times bordered on becoming unenjoyable and left a sense of confusion as to how AMA had not done a review of this course's quality.  this became quickly apparent when doing any of the assignments, short quizzes, long tests and especially the final exam. Questions sometimes were hard to answer, as some of the learned materials have overlapping information. 

  A question might ask a question that has multiple answers from differing groups of information altogether. The final exam was an egregiously excellent example of this, as it was vague on some questions that asked for answers that can come from different forms of sports, such as a question that applies for either badminton, table tennis or (long) tennis. 

  For the AMA staff and other members of the university, please consider a complete restructuring of this course, so that future students do not suffer from a frustrating experience.

column8: Some modules have several typographical errors.  The evaluation tools also have several erroneous questions especially on those questions with "double negative" questions.  The power point presentation was copied/pasted from the module then voice recorded by the teacher while reading the module including the typo errors.  She literally lifted everything from the module then copied it on the power point, including the errors, then added some pictures on it.  Some of the videos have very long "lag" or empty/muted content in the middle while waiting for the video PIP to play.  There were several acronyms in the module that were not explained in the content or provided its meaning.  For example, "report to your TRU or RCMP.  What is that??!? How are we going to report to them if this is an american-based security/dorm agency?  The modules should be revised to reflect real-time Philippine setting if not both to cater to all students from all over the world not just US-BASED settings or scenarios that most Filipino students can hardly relate.
column13: Mentor needs improvement in her presentation skills.  Most students can outdo the video presentation in the modules.  In real time school, we are not even allowed to copy and paste from our textbooks or the internet then simply paste it on our power point presentation.  Our Teachers should know better than to provide us with materials not only erroneous but lifted from online sources along with its typographical errors.  We expect more from our teachers if they expect more from us, students too.  They should practice what they preach or walk the talk.  Students nowadays can easily google everything and WE EXPECT TEACHERS TO HAVE BETTER CONTENT THAN WHAT WE HAVE JUST GOOGLED.  We expect to have at least a curated content from Google and other online sources.  Not typically lifted, copied and pasted along with the erroneous content. Very unprofessional and mediocre.

column8:
I regret to share my negative feedback regarding the computer programming subject I am currently taking. Unfortunately, my experience has been far from satisfactory, and I would like to outline the various issues I have encountered throughout the course.

Firstly, one of the major drawbacks was the consistently poor sound quality of the recorded classes. It became increasingly difficult to follow the lectures and grasp the concepts when the audio was unclear or distorted. This significantly hindered my ability to engage with the material and fully comprehend the topics being taught.

Furthermore, I found the professor's teaching style to be uninspiring and boring. The lack of enthusiasm and inability to effectively convey complex programming concepts made the learning process monotonous and unengaging. It is crucial for educators to create an engaging environment that stimulates students' interest and fosters a genuine desire to learn.

Another issue I encountered was the significant mismatch between the content taught in the course and the practical problems presented. The material covered did not adequately prepare us to tackle real-world programming challenges. As a result, I often felt ill-equipped and frustrated when trying to apply the knowledge gained from the course to solve practical problems.

column8: All is good Readable and easy to understand

1. Modules lesson should be straight to the point. Shorter modules are memorable compared to longer ones. include simple to understand summary of the entirety of the lesson. it does not have to be very short or very long.

2. consistency on text fonts in modules which sometimes can be hard to read.

3. All courses should be unlock even without the completion of the other weeks. So students can have an idea what to expect next or plan ahead of time. Example unlock Week 2 after the completion of week 1 Q&A.

4. Avoid using fill in the blanks when asking question and also the one that you need to arrange the answer this would cause problem and it complicates the system. Instead use a simple choices to answer the question not write them or arrange them.

5. Downloadable contents I don't know if I can download the contents or not but it would really help the students if they can download the modules so even if they have no access to internet they can study offline.


6. Memorization questions is fine but there are some question in some test that you need to answers fully to make it right. it is possible to create creative question when it is about memorization.

7.  Lack of Guided question on test some test have no guided questions that can confuse students. emphasize what to do give examples, highlight it at the beginning so students can clearly comprehend the task.

8. Accessing old courses I don't know if you can still access or read old courses taken after completing them. It is a good way to review even though I have my notes.

column8: All course module provide and references were relevant to the course

In order to enhance the online experience at AMA University Online Education, it is essential to expand the availability of references on the topics being discussed. A crucial step towards this goal is the development of an improved resource library that offers a comprehensive and easily accessible collection of reference materials, including e-books, research papers, articles, and videos. To enhance usability, these resources should be categorized based on subjects and topics, enabling students to locate relevant materials efficiently.

Furthermore, it would be beneficial to establish an online platform or forum dedicated to collaborative knowledge sharing. This platform would enable students to not only access existing references but also share additional learning materials and references related to the topics being discussed. By encouraging contributions from students, such as the ability to upload and share valuable resources they have discovered, a sense of community and cooperation would be fostered among the learners. This collaborative approach will enrich the learning experience and create a supportive environment for everyone involved.

Although, I have encountered a few problems in my quizzes and assignments as I've noticed that some questions have the wrong answers and made me confused.

For example; I encountered a fill in the blank question that asked "According to Fiverr research, demand for ____ increased by 72% in Italy.

1. Modules lesson should be straight to the point. Shorter modules are memorable compared to longer ones. include simple to understand summary of the entirety of the lesson. it does not have to be very short or very long.

2. consistency on text fonts in modules which sometimes can be hard to read.

3. All courses should be unlock even without the completion of the other weeks. So students can have an idea what to expect next or plan ahead of time. Example unlock Week 2 after the completion of week 1 Q&A.

4. Avoid using fill in the blanks when asking question and also the one that you need to arrange the answer this would cause problem and it complicates the system. Instead use a simple choices to answer the question not write them or arrange them. A simple true or false question is good compare to fill in the blank and it is challenging.

column8:
Also I have some suggestion about the contents and about all the tests.

1. Modules lesson should be straight to the point. Shorter modules are memorable compared to longer ones. include simple to understand summary of the entirety of the lesson. it does not have to be very short or very long.

2. consistency on text fonts in modules which sometimes can be hard to read.

3. All courses should be unlock even without the completion of the other weeks. So students can have an idea what to expect next or plan ahead of time. Example unlock Week 2 after the completion of week 1 Q&A.

4. Avoid using fill in the blanks when asking question and also the one that you need to arrange the answer this would cause problem and it complicates the system. Instead use a simple choices to answer the question not write them or arrange them. A simple true or false question is good compare to fill in the blank and it is challenging.

5. Downloadable contents I don't know if I can download the contents or not but it would really help the students if they can download the modules so even if they have no access to internet they can study offline.


6. Memorization questions is fine but there are some question in some test that you need to answers fully to make it right. it is possible to create creative question when it is about memorization.

7.  Lack of Guided question on test some test have no guided questions that can confuse students. emphasize what to do give examples, highlight it at the beginning so students can clearly comprehend the task.

8. Accessing old courses I don't know if you can still access or read old courses taken after completing them. It is a good way to review even though I have my notes.

9. Avoid using Lock Down Browser. Some subjects does not require lock down browser and some required I don't know why but it should be flexible system. where student could take note and learn.

The egregious grammatical errors and the poor structuring of the modules' writing has made the learning experience for the course less than optimal. 

While this may not be a major course, it was still disappointing to see that its content was not as comprehensive as it should have been. The content of the modules can often seem dogmatic as they are simply stated plainly (or with strange non-sequiturs, which I'll get to) without offering much in the way of counterargument from different perspectives. There are also strange asides, such as the one about Filipino Millennials, that are so tenuously connected to the topic being discussed in the module that you would think it was just added there for the sake of being topical. 

I still learned much from this course, and I believe with more refining it could build strong ethical foundations among students.

column8:
I think the one in charge may need to find a way to make the hyperlinks in the presentations work. They're mainly only in Lessons 1 and 10 with the rest being restricted to the references sections though. The link in Lesson 10 can be looked at in the module however.

Lessons 3-5 seem to be missing a video format and this might be because there was a switch in how the videos were made as the first two lessons had a person assigned to voice out the modules (not only in this course but also in the first few lessons of GE6101) while the rest used text-to speech. The human voiced videos are generally longer with the visuals resembling the presentations (but usually not exactly) while the text-to-speech voiced videos are generally shorter and were given completely new visuals not present in either the presentations or the modules. A slight downside with using text-to-speech would be how the voice can sometimes sound off which doesn't seem to be too evident here at least.

The modules are usually more complete than the presentations with some content featured in the modules being absent in the presentations. Sometimes, it's usually just the further explanations being omitted but in rare cases, entire sections can be completely absent as well.

I may have some suggestions for changes in some lessons.

Lesson 1:

A decision was apparently made to reword a lot of statements featured in the presentation when making the module. Sometimes, this may result in strange phrasing such as: 

Presentation: "He wanted to replace their final causal model of scientific explanation with the more modern, mechanistic model." (Slide 12)

Module: "Second, he needed to supplant their last causal model of logical clarification with the more current, robotic model." (Page 5)

Lesson 7: 

The video for this lesson only seems to cover less than half of the lesson for some reason as it stops after the "Different Cultural Perspectives on Femininity and Masculinity" section. I wonder if it might be because the rest of the lesson was added later on.

Lesson 8: 

Slides 6 & 7 in the presentation should be removed as the content in those slides were intended for Lesson 6.

Lesson 9: 

Strangely enough, slides 7 & 8 are actually exclusive to the presentation.

Lesson 13: 

I honestly have no idea what was going on here but for unknown reasons, the presentation has almost nothing in common to the video nor the module. This specific presentation may or may not need a complete overhaul to make it similar to the other two formats in this lesson.

Lesson 15: 

The objectives sections in both the presentation and the module have an out-of-place objective intended for Lesson 14. ("Identify types of approaches on how to be successful based on different psychologists.") The video doesn't seem to have this issue though.

column8:
Also I have some suggestion about the contents and about all the tests.

1. Modules lesson should be straight to the point. Shorter modules are memorable compared to longer ones. include simple to understand summary of the entirety of the lesson. it does not have to be very short or very long. 

2. consistency on text fonts in modules which sometimes can be hard to read.

3. All courses should be unlock even without the completion of the other weeks. So students can have an idea what to expect next or plan ahead of time. Example unlock Week 2 after the completion of week 1 Q&A.

4. Avoid using fill in the blanks when asking question and also the one that you need to arrange the answer this would cause problem and it complicates the system. Instead use a simple choices to answer the question not write them or arrange them. A simple true or false question is good compare to fill in the blank and it is challenging.

5. Downloadable contents I don't know if I can download the contents or not but it would really help the students if they can download the modules so even if they have no access to internet they can study offline.

6. Memorization questions is fine but there are some question in some test that you need to answers fully to make it right. it is possible to create creative question when it is about memorization.

7.  Lack of Guided question on test some test have no guided questions that can confuse students. emphasize what to do give examples, highlight it at the beginning so students can clearly comprehend the task.

8. Accessing old courses I don't know if you can still access or read old courses taken after completing them. It is a good way to review even though I have my notes.

9. Avoid using Lock Down Browser. Some subjects does not require lock down browser and some required I don't know why but it should be flexible system. where student could take note and learn.

10. Order of modules sometimes Week 1 questions will ask question that are not discuss yet.

11. Avoid using timers on short quizzes only to long quizz and finals.

column8:
This course is kind of an odd one in the sense that each of the lessons are mostly fairly empty on their own opting to mainly define terms and leaving them at that. It's not until the later lessons where some examples are actually shown to make certain topics easier to understand. The earlier topics are also given over a hundred supplementary links which do seem to expand on the topics provided at least. 

When it comes to the formats available for each lesson only the lessons in weeks 3 and 4 contain video lectures all of which containing the text-to-speech type of video lectures. The text-to-speech can sometimes sound funny whenever it tries to read the symbols due to how it works. Surprisingly, the lesson "Bonds and Bond Validation" doesn't contain a module which does make it fairly stand out.

I guess I'll end this with a few minor suggestions: 

"Mathematical Language and Symbols"
- Both the video lecture and the presentation are missing the section for "Existential Universal Statement". The video will unfortunately have to be redone with its current format being inflexible to edits but the presentation can at least be given an extra slide for it.

"Data Management"
- The image for the sample standard deviation equation in the module is a little bit misplaced as it's on the previous page. The presentation is also missing a slide for the z-scores.

"Compound Interest"
- The presentation did seem to cut off fairly early as it only talked about the definition of "Present Value" and didn't include the formulas and the example featured in the module.

"Mathematics of Graphs"
- Slide 7 in the presentation must be deleted at it's a slide intended for the lesson "Logic Statements and Quantifiers".

This seems to be another course alongside GE6100 - Understanding the Self where the same person was in charge of voicing the earlier video lectures although it's only for Lessons 1, 4, & 5 this time around. Lessons 2 & 3 don't have video lectures while the rest of the lessons use the newer format with text to speech. It's somewhat understandable for Lesson 3 to not have a video lecture in the old format since it's mainly just the entire text of a blog post. Lesson 1 also doesn't have a presentation format for some reason. 

Unfortunately, the text-to speech voice can sometimes sound strange at times. This is especially noticeable whenever it voices out non-English words as the voice was clearly not intended for them. Additionally, the later video lectures (starting from Lesson 11 with the exception of maybe Lesson 12) seem to be incomplete as they usually only cover the first few parts of each lesson. It's somewhat understandable since the last five lessons are very long.

Speaking of the last five lessons, for a set of lessons intended to be for a single week with a lot of sections intended for two weeks, there seems to be about as much to take a look at in this set of lessons when compared to the rest of the lessons combined. To put it into perspective, the eighteen modules have a total of 169 pages (which include the reference lists though) and 83 of them are in these five lessons alone. It took me three days just to finish reading the entire set which required spending the entirety of those days and an extra day to review. Lesson 14 in particular seemed to be really difficult to read despite being by far the shortest of the five. This seems to mainly come from the entire lesson not having any headers other than the ones at the beginning despite the lesson seemingly shifting to different topics once in a while. With these lessons being long, I was kind of glad the course project had been removed at some point prior to me taking this course.

(On an unrelated note: I had said I spent about 11-15 hours per week on average in this course but answered 30+ on the other courses. I made a mistake in those as I didn't notice it was "hours per week" and answered the amount I spent overall.)

These lessons also seemed to deviate from the pattern I noticed in the preceding lessons as many of those lessons seem to mainly come from a certain book in the reference list with a lot of the text either being copied and pasted verbatim (sometimes poorly with a few sentences being difficult to understand without looking for the text in the book) or outright being screenshots from said book. With that said, the lessons can sometimes contain other images as well.

A few of the lessons also had some questionable things such as these examples: 

Lesson 8: "...which honors the expedition's arrival and celebration of Mass on **April 8**, 1521."

(Screenshots from the book later on in this lesson state that the mass actually took place on March 31, 1521 which seems to be the correct date. This is also a question in some of the quizzes.)

Lesson 9: "In the year **1897** is a historic year of two events: the Cavite Mutiny...."

(The text later on in this lesson seem to correctly state the year as 1872. The original book also doesn't seem to contain this mistake so it's unknown what happened here.)

Lesson 12: "Since **1973** The Constitution of the Philippines has been in effect, it is the supreme law of the Republic of the Philippines." 

(While this is technically not incorrect as there was a 1973 Constitution, this sentence seem to refer to the current Constitution which is the one in **1987** .)

Regarding the quizzes, 
- Quiz 001 should be moved to before Lesson 3 as the quiz only contains questions for the first two lessons. 
- Quiz 005 has a question which is only answered in Lesson 14 which is not available until after the quiz is taken.

column8:
I like the "video lectures" that act as previews of what to expect during each lesson. While they don't actually teach the lessons themselves, they usually instead give examples of possible applications of each topic. 

The virtual class recordings are also quite nice here with some of them even showing different examples from the presentations and modules although some lessons can be absent in them once in a while. Additionally, there are no virtual class recordings for Weeks 12 & 13.

The presentations and the modules can sometimes leave a lot to be desired though. At first glance, it appears that the format seems to constantly change in the middle of each lesson. This is because the information there is actually copied word for word from the multiple sources being linked to (although some of the examples are modified slightly in the first few lessons). There isn't anything wrong with this per say but some slight inconsistencies have occurred as a result of simply copying the text without unifying them. For an example, in the third module of derivatives, there is a sub-topic called "Interpretations of the Derivative". It starts off by saying "Before moving on to the section where we learn how to compute derivatives by avoiding the limits we were evaluating in the previous section..." which may seem strange as this sub-topic is right after a lot of the rules for computing derivatives were taught. The reason why this statement exists though is because the the original source placed this lesson just after the topic for the definition of the derivative and before all the other derivative topics. 

Two of the sources used to make the modules (as stated in the reference lists of said modules) were...
- https://tutorial.math.lamar.edu/Classes/CalcI/CalcI.aspx
- https://sites.google.com/site/gkellymath/home/calculus-powerpoints
...and honestly, looking at these sources feel required especially at the later lessons which have the tendency to skip the harder examples in these sources but use variants of them in the assignments and quizzes anyway especially in the last week which was for Related Rates and Optimization Problems. Despite doing quite bad in the assessments for those lessons, I think I would have done worse had I not looked at the links before taking them.

The former link seems to be the basis for this entire course with the structure of said course being fairly identical to the first few categories of said link. There were a few lessons which were skipped such as the Definition of The Limit (probably for the best) which was only brought up briefly in one of the virtual class recordings and LÂHospitalÂs Rule (which I was honestly expecting to be the topic for Week 13 for some reason). The latter link seems to be used because the earlier presentations have the tendency to have questionable looking slides. Said link provides videos and even the presentations used in said videos where some of the slides were used for later lessons in this course.  

The final exam in particular also had a few questions for Logarithmic Differentiation which was not taught at any point in the entire course but was one of the lessons in the former link.

I suppose I have to also thank the presentations for Weeks 11 & 12 for giving advanced warnings for the lessons in Weeks 13 to make up for the presentations omitting some of the examples in their respective lessons.

As for the assignment and quizzes, it sometimes feels like I was running out of time to finish but that's more of my own issues than anything else. I think there were a few questions where I either got wrong or couldn't think of an answer due to typos in the question. Assignment 008 seems to be missing in the course as well. 

Some of the later lessons also mentioned some assessments to submit but it seems like all but the ones for Week 3 and the Course Project were removed. I will say that I would have probably not been able to finish the course had those assessments still existed.
column13:
I had actually communicated with the mentor through two tickets. One of which is to ask for clarification on whether I needed to print something and another is to inform about submitting the course project as well as one other thing. The response times were surprisingly good. 

The first ticket took about 1-2 days to get an answer but that could be a result of the ticket being sent to the wrong person.

The second ticket was solved adequately in an even faster time despite the same issue of the ticket being sent to the wrong person again (The tickets always seem to be sent to a random person for some unknown reasons). 

While it took longer than what I would have wanted (over 2 months) for the Week 3 assessments to be graded, after submitting the second ticket mentioning them, the assessments finally got graded. It made me feel like the mentor would have graded them had I sent a separate ticket about them earlier.

By the way, ignore the 3/5 rating for the "extra help" section. I didn't actually request for extra help so that rating can be considered as not applicable

column8: A sizeable portion of the educational material, and thus a portion of the final grade, consists of topics and subjects that were formerly relevant to the curriculum but are no longer necessary due to recent changes. Things I would like to suggest for improving the online experience would be  to establish a study timetable. This will assist us in maintaining organization and in taking pauses to prevent burnout. A Construct to-do lists. We won't be able to plan our daily or weekly study sessions or genuinely be productive without them. Please be specific with the time frames and actions you assign to each task on our to-do list. "Work on a project" is a vague notion that should be reserved for our mind mapping sessions rather than being an actual action.
Remain on course. The only thing left to do is to adhere to our study plan and to-do/deadline list once we have organized them. Time management is a crucial professional ability that online learning is teaching you, despite the fact that it sounds challenging and a little confused at first. All in all I enjoyed learning online in AMA University Online Education. God bless you more and thank you.

I am really grateful to have Sir Felanver M. Tonog as my mentor to help me improve my learning skills. In order for me to take more of what I learned I ask them to self-assess their learning in light of the unique and much approachable online learning environment.

I think adding different types of assignments besides quizzes could really boost our learning at AMA University Online. Like, doing research papers would let us dig deeper into topics, giving us a chance to really understand them well.
Essays are cool too because they help us practice putting our thoughts and ideas into words. It's a good way to show what we've learned.
Presentations might seem scary, but they're actually pretty neat. They help us get better at talking in front of others and explaining stuff clearly.
Having different kinds of assignments would make learning more interesting and help us learn in different ways. ItÂs not just about knowing stuff but also about being good at lots of skills that will help us in the future.
column13:
I feel like adding essays as part of our assessments would be really helpful. Quizzes are good, but essays let us show what we've really learned. They push us to think deeper about a topic and explain our ideas better. Plus, writing skills are super important, and essays would definitely help us improve that.

It'd be cool to have a mix of assessments, not just quizzes. Essays could bring out a different side of our learning and help us grow more.

column8: Kindly give at least 15 days free extension to access the courses when original access has ended.

Also I have some suggestion about the contents and about all the tests.

1. Modules lesson should be straight to the point. Shorter modules are memorable compared to longer ones. include simple to understand summary of the entirety of the lesson. it does not have to be very short or very long. 

2. consistency on text fonts in modules which sometimes can be hard to read.

3. All courses should be unlock even without the completion of the other weeks. So students can have an idea what to expect next or plan ahead of time. Example unlock Week 2 after the completion of week 1 Q&A.

4. Avoid using fill in the blanks when asking question and also the one that you need to arrange the answer this would cause problem and it complicates the system. Instead use a simple choices to answer the question not write them or arrange them. A simple true or false question is good compare to fill in the blank and it is challenging.

5. Downloadable contents I don't know if I can download the contents or not but it would really help the students if they can download the modules so even if they have no access to internet they can study offline.

6. Memorization questions is fine but there are some question in some test that you need to answers fully to make it right. it is possible to create creative question when it is about memorization.

7.  Lack of Guided question on test some test have no guided questions that can confuse students. emphasize what to do give examples, highlight it at the beginning so students can clearly comprehend the task.

8. Accessing old courses I don't know if you can still access or read old courses taken after completing them. It is a good way to review even though I have my notes.

9. Avoid using Lock Down Browser. Some subjects does not require lock down browser and some required I don't know why but it should be flexible system. where student could take note and learn.

10. Order of modules sometimes Week 1 questions will ask question that are not discuss yet.

11. Avoid using timers on short quizzes only to long quizz and finals.

12. Less History lesson and more on the current knowledge.

I suggest that the course provides a comprehensive procedural approach that provides an initial discussion of the tools and requirements of Windows server systems and how to install these systems. Then and only then, may it discuss on installing these specified server installations as these may help provide more emphasis on the necessary tools for the process.

column8:
Overall, the content presented in this course was informative and well-structured. However, I believe that the course could be further enhanced by providing simpler explanations and examples. Similar to how LinkedIn Learning presents materials, the course content could be made more concise and easier to follow.

Additionally, providing sample codes through the Learning Management System (LMS) or GitHub would greatly benefit students. This would allow them to have hands-on experience and follow along while watching the video tutorials. Having a tangible example to refer to while learning would greatly enhance understanding and retention of the material. 

I noticed a few grammar errors in the laboratory exercises and course module, which hindered my ability to fully understand the goal of the activity. Accuracy and attention to detail in written instructions are crucial to ensure clarity and comprehension among students.

Some of the grammatical errors in the module and questions have made it very confusing for me. There were even a couple of instances where the questions given were from the next module, so it wasn't covered yet. Also, it would be great to have essay questions instead of multiple choice questions so as to give students the opportunity to use their own words / explain in their own way, their understanding of the topics discussed.

The Final Exam questions were basically asking students to just memorize every single sentence in the module, word per word, instead of actually encouraging students to explain and answer in their own words (essay format), which would then show what and how much they've understood in the entire course. Also, there were so many grammatical errors, which made it very hard to understand what the question really was about. Big improvements needed as this directly reflects the standard of the Philippine Education System. Please look into this, asap. Thank you.

column8:
Also I have some suggestion about the contents and about all the tests.

1. Modules lesson should be straight to the point. Shorter modules are memorable compared to longer ones. include simple to understand summary of the entirety of the lesson. it does not have to be very short or very long. 

2. consistency on text fonts in modules which sometimes can be hard to read.

3. All courses should be unlock even without the completion of the other weeks. So students can have an idea what to expect next or plan ahead of time. Example unlock Week 2 after the completion of week 1 Q&A.

4. Avoid using fill in the blanks when asking question and also the one that you need to arrange the answer this would cause problem and it complicates the system. Instead use a simple choices to answer the question not write them or arrange them. A simple true or false question is good compare to fill in the blank and it is challenging.

5. Downloadable contents I don't know if I can download the contents or not but it would really help the students if they can download the modules so even if they have no access to internet they can study offline.

6. Memorization questions is fine but there are some question in some test that you need to answers fully to make it right. it is possible to create creative question when it is about memorization.

7.  Lack of Guided question on test some test have no guided questions that can confuse students. emphasize what to do give examples, highlight it at the beginning so students can clearly comprehend the task.

8. Accessing old courses I don't know if you can still access or read old courses taken after completing them. It is a good way to review even though I have my notes.

9. Avoid using Lock Down Browser. Some subjects does not require lock down browser and some required I don't know why but it should be flexible system. where student could take note and learn.

10. Order of modules sometimes Week 1 questions will ask question that are not discuss yet.

11. Avoid using timers on short quizzes only to long quizz and finals.

12. Less History lesson and more on the current knowledge.

column8:
Also I have some suggestion about the contents and about all the tests.

1. Modules lesson should be straight to the point. Shorter modules are memorable compared to longer ones. include simple to understand summary of the entirety of the lesson. it does not have to be very short or very long. 

2. consistency on text fonts in modules which sometimes can be hard to read.

3. All courses should be unlock even without the completion of the other weeks. So students can have an idea what to expect next or plan ahead of time. Example unlock Week 2 after the completion of week 1 Q&A.

4. Avoid using fill in the blanks when asking question and also the one that you need to arrange the answer this would cause problem and it complicates the system. Instead use a simple choices to answer the question not write them or arrange them. A simple true or false question is good compare to fill in the blank and it is challenging.

5. Downloadable contents I don't know if I can download the contents or not but it would really help the students if they can download the modules so even if they have no access to internet they can study offline.

6. Memorization questions is fine but there are some question in some test that you need to answers fully to make it right. it is possible to create creative question when it is about memorization.

7.  Lack of Guided question on test some test have no guided questions that can confuse students. emphasize what to do give examples, highlight it at the beginning so students can clearly comprehend the task.

8. Accessing old courses I don't know if you can still access or read old courses taken after completing them. It is a good way to review even though I have my notes.

9. Avoid using Lock Down Browser. Some subjects does not require lock down browser and some required I don't know why but it should be flexible system. where student could take note and learn.

10. Order of modules sometimes Week 1 questions will ask question that are not discuss yet.

11. Avoid using timers on short quizzes only to long quizz and finals.

12. Less History lesson and more on the current knowledge.

column8:
Also I have some suggestion about the contents and about all the tests.

1. Modules lesson should be straight to the point. Shorter modules are memorable compared to longer ones. include simple to understand summary of the entirety of the lesson. it does not have to be very short or very long. 

2. consistency on text fonts in modules which sometimes can be hard to read.

3. All courses should be unlock even without the completion of the other weeks. So students can have an idea what to expect next or plan ahead of time. Example unlock Week 2 after the completion of week 1 Q&A.

4. Avoid using fill in the blanks when asking question and also the one that you need to arrange the answer this would cause problem and it complicates the system. Instead use a simple choices to answer the question not write them or arrange them. A simple true or false question is good compare to fill in the blank and it is challenging.

5. Downloadable contents I don't know if I can download the contents or not but it would really help the students if they can download the modules so even if they have no access to internet they can study offline.

6. Memorization questions is fine but there are some question in some test that you need to answers fully to make it right. it is possible to create creative question when it is about memorization.

7.  Lack of Guided question on test some test have no guided questions that can confuse students. emphasize what to do give examples, highlight it at the beginning so students can clearly comprehend the task.

8. Accessing old courses I don't know if you can still access or read old courses taken after completing them. It is a good way to review even though I have my notes.

9. Avoid using Lock Down Browser. Some subjects does not require lock down browser and some required I don't know why but it should be flexible system. where student could take note and learn.

10. Order of modules sometimes Week 1 questions will ask question that are not discuss yet.

11. Avoid using timers on short quizzes only to long quizz and finals.

12. Less History lesson and more on the current knowledge.

I have learned that Prof. Shannen Quernell Angeles is no longer associated with AMA OEd, yet her recorded video lessons are still available. Her profile is still use in the Course. While I acknowledge that this program is designed for self-paced study, I believe that students deserve more high-quality lessons with in-depth explanations and examples from professors, rather than simply being presented and read with what's already written in the module. column8:
Improving the online experience at AMA University Online Education could involve several strategies to enhance user engagement, accessibility, and overall satisfaction. Here are some suggestions:

User-Friendly Interface: Ensure that the online platform has an intuitive and user-friendly interface. Navigation should be simple and logical, with clear menus and instructions.

Mobile Optimization: With the increasing use of mobile devices, optimize the platform for mobile users. This includes responsive design and a mobile app for easy access to course materials and communication tools.

Interactive Content: Incorporate interactive elements such as quizzes, polls, and multimedia content to make the learning experience more engaging and dynamic.

Personalized Learning Paths: Implement adaptive learning technologies that tailor course content and assignments to individual student needs and learning styles.

Community Building: Foster a sense of community among students and faculty through discussion forums, group projects, and virtual events. Encourage collaboration and peer-to-peer support.

Real-Time Support: Offer live chat support and virtual office hours to provide timely assistance to students and address any technical or academic concerns they may have.

Feedback Mechanism: Establish a feedback mechanism where students can provide input on courses, instructors, and the overall online learning experience. Use this feedback to continually improve and refine the platform.

Accessibility Features: Ensure that the online platform complies with accessibility standards, making it usable for students with disabilities. This includes providing alternative formats for course materials and accommodating assistive technologies.

Gamification: Integrate gamification elements such as badges, rewards, and leaderboards to incentivize student engagement and progress through the courses.

Regular Updates and Maintenance: Keep the online platform up-to-date with the latest technologies and features. Perform regular maintenance to address any technical issues and ensure smooth functionality.

Data Analytics: Use data analytics to track student progress, identify areas for improvement, and measure the effectiveness of online courses and instructional methods.

Integration with Learning Management Systems: Integrate the online platform with popular learning management systems (LMS) such as Moodle or Canvas to streamline course management and content delivery.

By implementing these suggestions, AMA University Online Education can create a more dynamic, interactive, and user-centered online learning environment that enhances student satisfaction and success.
column13:
Enhance Communication Channels: Ensure that there are clear and efficient communication channels established between students and mentors. Encourage regular updates, feedback sessions, and Q&A sessions to address student concerns and provide guidance.

Provide Timely Feedback: Timely feedback is crucial for student learning and motivation. Encourage mentors to provide prompt and constructive feedback on assignments, assessments, and inquiries from students.

Promote Active Engagement: Encourage mentors to promote active engagement among students through interactive discussions, group projects, and collaborative activities. This helps foster a sense of community and enhances the learning experience.

Offer Support Resources: Ensure that mentors are equipped with the necessary resources and tools to support students effectively. This includes access to learning materials, tutorials, and support documentation.

Encourage Accessibility and Inclusivity: Emphasize the importance of creating an inclusive learning environment that accommodates students with diverse backgrounds, abilities, and learning needs. Encourage mentors to be mindful of accessibility considerations and provide support for all students.

Promote Professional Development: Encourage mentors to engage in ongoing professional development opportunities to enhance their teaching skills, knowledge of online pedagogy, and familiarity with emerging technologies.

Foster Mentor-Student Relationships: Encourage mentors to build strong relationships with their students by being approachable, supportive, and responsive to their needs. Encourage regular check-ins and one-on-one sessions to provide personalized guidance and support.

Monitor Student Progress: Encourage mentors to actively monitor student progress and performance throughout the course. This allows them to identify struggling students early on and provide targeted interventions to support their success.

Seek Feedback from Students: Encourage mentors to regularly solicit feedback from students about their learning experience, including what is working well and areas for improvement. Use this feedback to make continuous improvements to the online learning environment.

Stay Updated with Best Practices: Encourage mentors to stay updated with best practices in online education, instructional design, and student engagement strategies. Provide opportunities for mentors to share insights and learn from each other.

By implementing these suggestions, mentors can play a critical role in enhancing the online learning experience at AMA University and supporting student success.

column8: Give the course project earlier in the beginning of the course. Or don't lock it so we can work on it in advance.

This course consists of two types of video lectures: the video lectures inside the lessons, and the virtual class recordings accessible outside. 

Most of the inside video lectures seem to mainly consist of reading straight from a script (I think some of the earlier ones used the module as the script) but there were a few such as the ones for Weeks 5-7 as well as the second video lecture of Week 10 which deviate from that. These usually involve either showcasing a certain program related to the lesson such as Microsoft Word (Week 5), Excel (Week 6), and Powerpoint (Week 7) or showing how to write a basic HTML program using a text editor (Week 10).

As for the virtual classes, the ones available seem to be fine although the one for Week 2 is almost entirely a collection of YouTube videos each consisting of how to convert from a specific number system to another number system. Surprisingly, none of those videos are in the reference list of the lessons. Unfortunately, those recordings stopped after Week 5. The one who made those recordings mentioned that there will be recordings just that there will no longer be live classes but it seems like those recordings never existed anyway.  Considering the last virtual class was in 2022, it's very unlikely they will ever come.

I don't really have much to say about the presentations and the modules. With that said, it's a little funny how the slide that says to limit the number of bullet points in a slide to three to five (which is a good advice for a presentation slide) has six bullet points and is also one of the most word heavy slides in this course. It seems like that slide needs to take its own advice but that's really it.

column8:
For a single-unit course, there was surprisingly more to do than I expected. It did make me realize that the number of laboratory units in a course can only be either 0 or 1. With that said, I don't really have much to say here. 

There are no modules this time around but the presentations seem to suffice. The recorded virtual classes feature the presentations with slight alterations and more explanation giving them some use. The lessons also feature some YouTube videos which could be useful when doing the drawing activities. With that said, the instructions can be a little unclear at times but asking the mentor can solve that issue.
column13: One thing I can at least say is that the mentor was able to answer some confusions I had with the activities.

column8:
One thing I'll say is that the course does what it needs to do at least. Eight of the ten lessons are mainly taken straight from the college handbook. The course consists of only modules (it doesn't seem like there is any need for the other types of material), some quizzes, and a few activities here and there. 

One big change I will suggest is to completely replace the lesson containing the "LMS Manual" to reflect the current portal being used. I already question the idea of locking something like this behind a course but the manual seems to assume an older version of an AMA OED site. 

I think the course can also benefit by showing signs that this course must be taken early as well as I wouldn't have guessed from the course name that it's mostly about the college handbook.

column8:
For a course being labelled as a two-unit course, I wasn't expecting the amount of module pages to read to be more than than the amount of module pages I read in all the courses I took in the previous term combined. With that said, I think the long modules did manage to make the course as detailed as it could be despite how tedious it was to get through them all. 

I would not suggest trimming down the content at all, from what I've noticed it appears that a lot of the activities were already cut earlier and it looks like two of the presentations were removed even though the modules clearly show a few presentation slides from said presentations. 

There are two types of video lectures. The ones inside the lessons are mainly the modules but voiced with the presentations featured being slightly different from the presentations given as material. The virtual class recordings act as shorter supplemental videos which can sometimes become very different to the modules at times. With that said, some of the minor quizzes might test for those making it a bad idea to skip those materials.

Another thing to note is that one of the videos, "Complete Workout #1", has an issue where it doesn't load past the 19:04 mark.

column8:
I recently completed the online Purposive Communication course, and I wanted to provide some feedback on my experience. Overall, I found the course to be informative and well-structured. The content was presented in a clear and concise manner, making it easy to understand and follow along.

One aspect that I particularly appreciated was the use of real-life examples and practical exercises throughout the course. This allowed me to apply the concepts I learned to real-world situations, which enhanced my understanding and retention of the material.

The course materials were also well-organized and easily accessible. The online platform was user-friendly, providing smooth navigation and easy access to course resources. The video lectures and supplementary materials were of high quality and helped to reinforce the course content.

Furthermore, the instructor was knowledgeable and engaging. They were responsive to questions and provided timely feedback on assignments and quizzes. Their expertise in the subject matter was evident, and their teaching style kept me engaged throughout the course.

One area for improvement could be the inclusion of more interactive elements, such as group discussions . This could enhance the learning experience by promoting collaboration and allowing for immediate feedback and clarification.

Overall, I am satisfied with the Online Education Purposive Communication course. It provided me with valuable knowledge and skills that I can apply in both personal and professional settings. I would highly recommend this course to anyone looking to improve their communication skills.

column8: Please explain more about the modules

1. Enhancement of Course Materials: The course could be significantly improved by incorporating additional reading materials, such as textbooks. This is crucial considering that the exam questions are not exclusively derived from the video lectures.

2. Teaching Style Adjustment: The video lectures predominantly utilize anecdotes as a teaching method, which can be time-consuming. While anecdotes can offer valuable context, a more direct approach featuring concrete examples and applications may expedite learning, particularly for mature students. There are alternative introductory courses available in LinkedIn that present the topic of intelligent systems in a more digestible manner, with an emphasis on programming examples and applications.

column8:
The course materials are in dire need of a rework. There are a lot of fascinating and complex topics here relevant to my field of study, but it's hard to parse the materials because:
- The audio-visual modules (or what little we have of those) are poorly executed. Presentation slides are crammed with too much information instead of being given the space to breathe, and video modules are narrated by someone who's not terribly confident and proficient in their delivery, plus the background noise in some of these videos was so awful as to be downright distracting.
- The overall course needed some proofreading. It's difficult to understand most of the course material because whoever wrote them wasn't proficient in English, not to mention that typos and formatting errors abound, even in quizzes. Some modules are nothing but massive walls of confusing and incomprehensible text where a lot of complex jargon gets tossed around without much thought or care.
- Information was regurgitated at the student with little thought or care. Again, these are complex and fascinating topics, and whoever put these together is likely an expert in the field, but the creator/s of these materials fails to organize and simplify the information for students who are only just starting to learn about these concepts.

Overall I've come out of this course confused and frustrated. At this point I feel better served just doing online research for free rather than having paid for this course.
Provide more learning materials and lectures.

column8: To enhance the online learning experience at AMA University, several improvements can be implemented. Firstly, video lectures should offer deeper insights into the course material by providing explanations beyond what is presented in the modules.  Especially in a course focused on "Understanding the Self," incorporating relevant real-life experiences and examples can significantly improve understanding and application of principles. Additionally, including self-reflection questionnaires into quizzes can promote introspection and a better understanding of oneself within the context of the course content. These improvement not only enrich learning but also foster personal growth and self-awareness among students.
column13: I have some suggestions for how my mentor could improve my online experience at AMA University Online Education,  even though I haven't reached out to them directly. First off, incorporating more personalized touches in video lectures by speaking in their own voice instead of relying solely on AI-generated content could make the learning experience feel more engaging and relatable. Moreover, integrating real-life experiences and stories related to the topics discussed can help solidify understanding and application of concepts. Additionally, ensuring that all lessons have accompanying video lectures can be beneficial, as it allows for a multi-modal approach to learning where I can absorb information from both reading the module and watching the mentor's explanations simultaneously.

column8: To improve the online learning experience at AMA University, video lectures must be included into all modules. These videos should go deeper into the issues and provide more than just a reiteration of the module's material. Instead, they should provide thorough explanations supplemented with real-life scenarios and examples in order to create a greater understanding of the subject. By introducing real-world applications, students can connect theoretical concepts to actual life situations, improving comprehension and recall. This multimodal approach not only accommodates different learning styles, but also creates a more engaging and effective learning environment for students from multiple fields.
column13: For a better online experience at AMA University, mentors could focus on providing concise, easy-to-understand modules instead of lengthy excerpts from research papers. Incorporating video lectures that delve deeper into topics and offer real-world examples would enhance comprehension and engagement. Additionally, mentors could direct students to supplementary learning materials or present scenarios to show practical applications, resulting in a more effective learning process. By taking these steps, mentors can significantly contribute to improving the overall online learning experience for students.

Engaging in local discussions on investment analysis provides valuable insights tailored to the unique economic and regulatory landscape of the Philippines. By focusing on local scenarios, we can gain a clearer understanding of market dynamics, regional opportunities, and specific challenges that may not be apparent from a broader perspective. While knowledge of foreign investment practices is certainly beneficial and can offer comparative insights, it is crucial to appreciate the particularities of the Philippine investment environment. Local discussions can address factors such as local regulations, market trends, and cultural nuances that significantly impact investment decisions. This localized approach not only enhances the relevance of investment strategies but also fosters a deeper comprehension of how to navigate and capitalize on opportunities within the Philippine market.
column13: The absence of a mentor in the Learning Management System (LMS) has been a notable challenge, especially given the complexity and depth required for mastering our specialization. There aren't any major issues I can think of for this course. The course feels mostly complete. The laboratory exercises seem decent enough although the instructions for what to do for a few programs can be a little too vague. The presentations mainly give an example program starting from Week 005. The video lectures (beside the first few which are rehashes of the presentations), seem to also show their own set of codes. The modules seem to show just enough information to make sense while also letting me solve the laboratory exercises on my own. The virtual class recordings also go through the modules but seem to also show maybe a few things exclusive to it. From what I understand, programming seems to consist of knowing the basics and then searching for anything else when needed. With that in mind, I think the course seem to do its job well.
column13: The feedback for the mentor seems to be alright although I wasn't able to make use of one of them due to it showing up late. column8: A lot of the time spent for the course seems to be mostly for the virtual class recordings. They seem to present new material at least. The course being related to communications means a lot of the time was spent on classmates featured in the recordings recalling their experiences. Make no mistake. This is not a negative in any way. The optional reading materials are fine although I'm pretty sure some of the links in the first (reading material) link don't work anymore. The first two lessons contain video lectures which are in about the same style as the earlier ones in GE6100 and GE6101. The presentations can sometimes contain images which are not present in the modules. Weirdly enough, the link for the presentations in Lesson 1 & Lesson 2 both contain content for Lesson 2 (they use different links and even have different names). column13: (Completely disregard all ratings for this category as there have been no interactions done between the student and the mentor.)

column8: If I'm honest, the presentations and modules (they contain the same content), don't really seem too useful here. I seem to rely more on outside material and may have only done fairly well in this course due to watching videos of most of the lessons here months before taking this course. Their only purpose seems to be to just give more examples which I have a hard time understanding without attempting to solve them myself. The presentations are also probably not recommended due to some text overlapping each other such as some slides in the presentation for the lesson: "Transformation of Trigonometric Integrals". Some lessons seem to contain video lessons which consist of the mentor showing the solutions featured in the presentations while also solving said integrals himself which is admittedly easier to understand. The later ones only feature some of the earlier examples. They also seem to show something a little interesting in particular. It kind of looks like the mentor has no control on what is shown in the presentation. This seems to be evident in the video lesson for "Area Between Curves". The mentor seemed to have only realized the first example had an incorrect answer and spent about 10 minutes rechecking an area which just so happens to be the only one which doesn't require integration to solve since it's a triangle. Another strange thing also happened regarding video lessons. The links for the video lessons for Weeks 3 & 4 both lead to the one for the latter (they also seem to be the same link). Additionally, the last 10 minutes were completely muted with the mentor not being able to notice. Some of the lessons stated in the description of the course also seem to be absent. column8:
The course overall was commendable; however, I would like to suggest a more pronounced emphasis on the mathematical components of the curriculum. To enhance the online learning experience, the inclusion of supplementary resources such as video tutorials and relevant articles could significantly deepen students' comprehension of the material.

Moreover, expanding the variety of practice problems, coupled with immediate feedback mechanisms, would greatly facilitate self-assessment and mastery of concepts. The establishment of dedicated discussion forums specifically for mathematics-related topics would promote collaboration and foster a supportive peer learning environment.

Additionally, inviting guest lecturers who are experts in applied mathematics could provide invaluable real-world context, enriching the learning experience further. Implementing these improvements could create a more robust and engaging educational experience for all participants.
column13: I would like to commend Professor Cariaso for his responsiveness to student inquiries and concerns, which significantly enriches our learning environment. To further enhance our educational experience and the quality of our outputs, I recommend the provision of comprehensive and detailed feedback on our case studies and reaction papers. Given the inherently subjective nature of these assignments, thorough comments would be invaluable in guiding our understanding and refining our analytical skills. Such feedback should highlight both strengths and areas for improvement, thereby fostering deeper engagement with the material and promoting personal and academic growth. Implementing this approach would not only enhance our learning outcomes but also cultivate our development as critical thinkers.

column8: The course is fully equipped with modules

Most of the course modules were very informative, easy on the eyes, and very digestible. The modules were factual and quite comprehensive as well. However, some information needs to be updated/corrected, like the number of islands in the Philippines; or perhaps provide more information like for example, that pre-colonial barangays ranged from small communities to large complex polities; week 02 module also didn't specify whether the deities were Tagalog, Kapampangan, Visayan, etc.; it also failed to provide the differences between the social classes/structures of the Tagalogs, Visayans, etc. and that Datus had different titles. However, I appreciate how comprehensive some of the modules were. Like for example, week 03 module shed some light on cultural syncretism by pointing out that Filipino Catholicism is a blend of indigenous paganism and Roman Catholicism, which may be new information to students who are not that interested in our cultural history; Week 08 module was also objective and did not leave out the the economic downfall of the Philippines during and the corruption, cronyism, and mismanagement of the Marcos regime which are facts. However, it also needs to be updated for the module ends with the PNoy Administration.

Course title is misleading. Popular culture refers to cultural aspects (beliefs, practices, values, objects, artistic outputs) that are dominant or prevalent in a society. This includes literature, film, TV, music, sports, politics, fashion, technology, slang, etc. Given the title, I thought we will be diving into Philippine popular culture and see how it reflects and/or affect our political landscape. I humbly suggest that the course be renamed and that the title must instead reflect the content/topics of the course which were mainly about Philippine geography; the cultural and political evolution of the Philippines from pre-colonial to colonial to now; the Presidents of the Philippines; and the Constitution (rights, government structure).
