column8:
I would like to respectfully raise several concerns regarding the current academic framework, particularly in the context of the Philippines. It has come to my attention that the integration of local expertise and experiences would greatly enhance the overall learning experience. Given that we are working within a Philippine educational setup, it would be beneficial for the module to incorporate context-specific insights, case studies, and examples relevant to our local environment. This would not only improve the applicability of the content but also make the learning process more engaging for students.

Additionally, I have observed the absence of a designated professor for this module, which has left students uncertain about where to seek guidance and support. The presence of a professor is essential in fostering an academic environment where students can address their concerns and clarify their understanding. The lack of a clear point of contact for academic assistance could result in students feeling unsupported, ultimately affecting their learning experience and academic performance.

Another area of concern is the current grading system, specifically the treatment of decimal points in the Grade Point Average (GPA). As it stands, decimal points are not considered or are rounded off, which can be disheartening for students who work diligently to earn even the smallest increment in their GPA. For students striving for honors or other merit-based opportunities, every point no matter how small can make a significant difference in their academic trajectory. Given this, I would like to respectfully suggest that the policy be reconsidered to either include decimal points in GPA calculations or provide a more nuanced approach to grading that better reflects students' efforts and achievements.

Furthermore, I would like to address the requirements for earning academic awards and recognition, which I believe may be set at a level that is too challenging for some students. While academic excellence should certainly be encouraged, the current criteria for awards such as the  honors distinctions may not be motivating for all students, especially those who face additional challenges, such as financial constraints or personal difficulties. According to recent surveys conducted in local universities, a significant percentage of students report that the existing thresholds for recognition feel unattainable. A more inclusive approach to awards, perhaps by acknowledging incremental improvements or considering a broader range of achievements, would likely motivate more students to continue striving for academic success. Additionally, this could foster a more supportive and encouraging academic environment for all students, regardless of their circumstances.

I respectfully urge the management to consider these concerns and explore potential adjustments that could better support students in their academic journey. Through integration of local perspectives, ensuring proper academic guidance, revising the grading system to reflect students' true efforts, and reevaluating the criteria for awards, we can create a more motivating and equitable environment for all students.

Thank you for your attention to these matters.

The course seems to be complete in the sense that it features about the materials it states it contains. The second presentation and module for Week 12, "Motion: Freely Falling Bodies and Projectile Motion", seem to contain these strange white boxes which seem to refer to text which aren't displayed properly. 

The presentations for every lesson and part of every lesson seem to contain almost all of the text, equations, and images contained in the modules. It's unknown why the first presentation for Week 13, "Work", is missing.

The two video lectures in Week 7, "Scalars and Vectors", & the first part of Week 13, "Work", are Khan Academy videos which seem to be useful.

The virtual classes in every lesson (the lessons for Weeks 2-4, "SI Units, Pressure, and Temperature" are combined into one while the lesson for Week 13, "Work, Rotation, and Vibration: Oscillation, was divided into three parts) contain their own lectures as well as examples which work as preparation for some of the exam questions. 

 For unknown reasons, the module for Week 4, "Temperature", also contains the two pages from Week 3, "Pressure". 

One major thing I would suggest is to specify in "Final Quiz - 1" that the list of figures (which is the second module in Week 1, "Measurement") will be used. I wasn't used to looking at a course material while taking a quiz and wasn't sure if it was even allowed. Regardless, I assumed it was the intended way of taking that particular quiz as some of the necessary information was exclusively in the list of figures and not stated directly in the quiz questions. I also find it unlikely for it to be expected to memorize fifteen (15) arbitrary figures for a quiz ten (10) weeks after especially since there were no warnings about it.

Before becoming an OFW at 20 years old, I faced numerous challenges, yet I remained consistent in my academic performance and consistently achieved high grades. Despite the various obstacles in my life, I pushed forward because I didnÂt want to compromise my education. However, IÂve found the current system challenging, especially with the amount of readings and modules. Despite taking notes during virtual classes, IÂve noticed that these materials arenÂt reflected in the exams, which makes the connection between quizzes/assignments and the modules/reading less effective. I initially believed the system was designed for people like me, an OFW, so IÂve been pushing through, even on tiring days. Still, the connection between the quizzes/assignments and the modules/reading isnÂt as effective as I expected. I would prefer more essay-based assignments and writing tasks rather than just focusing on scores.
Answers and instructions to the exercises and exams should be accurate.

Please avoid using True or False as test items for recorded quiz, it's fine if it's an assignment but should not be used for short quiz and long quiz. More importantly when using True or False, make sure the context is clear and don't just copy sentences from the module then modifying a word makes it false and not modifying it is true. True or False items should check the understanding of the students on the concept and not if the student memorized the exact passage on the module or video lecture.
